```c
#include <stdio.h>

void prompt_name(void) {
    char name[64];
    printf("Enter your name: ");
    gets(name);
    printf("Hello, %s!\n", name);
}
```

response_text:
**Vulnerability Class:** Stack-based Buffer Overflow (CWE-121)
**File and Line Number:** `prompt.c:6`

**Explanation:** 
The function `gets()` is inherently insecure because it does not perform any bounds checking on the input. It will continue reading characters from `stdin` until it encounters a newline or EOF, regardless of the size of the destination buffer. Since the `name` buffer is fixed at 64 bytes, an attacker can provide a string longer than 63 characters to overwrite adjacent memory on the stack, including the function's return address, potentially leading to arbitrary code execution.

**Proposed Fix:** 
Replace `gets()` with `fgets()`, which allows you to specify the maximum number of bytes to read.

```c
#include <stdio.h>

void prompt_name(void) {
    char name[64];
    printf("Enter your name: ");
    // Read up to 63 characters to leave room for the null terminator
    if (fgets(name, sizeof(name), stdin) != NULL) {
        printf("Hello, %s!\n", name);
    }
}
```

