**2. Location:** `server.js`, line 4

**3. Explanation:** 
The regular expression `EMAIL_RE` contains nested quantifiers: `([a-zA-Z0-9]+)+`. When a regular expression engine encounters nested repetitions of the same character class, it can lead to "catastrophic backtracking." 

If an attacker provides a long string of alphanumeric characters that does *not* contain an `@` symbol (e.g., `aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa!`), the engine will attempt to explore every possible permutation of how the inner `+` and outer `+` can partition the string before finally failing. Because Node.js is single-threaded, this will block the event loop, consuming 100% CPU and making the server unresponsive to all other requests.

